10
00:00:37,711 --> 00:00:40,493
the same name for the capsule,
the Soyuz capsule.

11
00:00:40,493 --> 00:00:42,958
By the way, you see
the so-called "escape tower"

12
00:00:42,958 --> 00:00:44,447
on top of the Soyuz capsule,

13
00:00:44,447 --> 00:00:47,032
in case there is
any problem during launch,

14
00:00:47,032 --> 00:00:52,522
for instance, a Soyuz rocket failure
or an explosion,

15
00:00:52,522 --> 00:00:56,339
then there is a possibility for the crew
to trigger an escape.

16
00:00:56,339 --> 00:00:58,489
There are some rockets
on this escape tower

17
00:00:58,489 --> 00:01:02,257
that can be fired
and take the Soyuz capsule,

18
00:01:02,257 --> 00:01:04,996
together with the three crew members
on board, to some distance

19
00:01:04,996 --> 00:01:07,150
and then they come down
with parachutes on the ground.

20
00:01:07,150 --> 00:01:10,186
So there is a very valuable
escape system on Soyuz.

21
00:01:10,837 --> 00:01:13,860
This is a Soyuz capsule
with three crew members on board,

22
00:01:13,860 --> 00:01:17,222
coming in the vicinity
of the International Space Station.

23
00:01:17,222 --> 00:01:22,078
The nominal approach, and docking
of the Soyuz capsule to ISS

24
00:01:22,078 --> 00:01:26,098
is all automatic, and you see here
various sensors and antennas,

25
00:01:26,098 --> 00:01:29,369
and sensors and cameras
